Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new board members for the U.S. central bank, the Federal Reserve, gives Americans – and the U.S. Congress – the opportunity to reflect on the world's most important central bank and its future path.
The obvious question that needs to be addressed first is how the Fed failed so miserably in fulfilling its most important mandate – ensuring price stability.
The fact that the Fed was completely caught off guard by current inflation points to a fundamental failure.
Now, it is undoubtedly time for institutional soul-searching.
But while monetary policy makes headlines, the Fed is now primarily significant as a financial regulator.
A major question therefore arises as to whether it will use its enormous power to advance climate or social policy.
For example, the Fed could refuse loans to companies in the fossil fuel sector, it could require banks to grant credit only to firms with certified net-zero emission plans, or it could steer lending towards desired alternatives.
Furthermore, it could decide to explicitly incorporate regulation in the name of equality or ethnic justice, by prescribing to banks where and to whom loans should be granted, who should be hired and who fired, and so on.
But before we turn to the question of which direction Fed regulation will take or should take, it is first necessary to clarify the Fed's grave failure.
In 2008, the U.S. government made a crucial decision: Financial institutions could continue to finance risky investments primarily through the sale of short-term, highly sensitive debt instruments, but armies of new regulatory bodies would henceforth assess the risk sensitivity of the institution's assets.
The hope was that these regulatory bodies would no longer overlook large chunks like those of subprime mortgages on bank balance sheets.
Yet, over the subsequent ten years of detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the Fed's army of regulators never once questioned what would happen in the event of a pandemic.
When the pandemic did indeed arrive at the beginning of 2020, the Fed abandoned its "never again" promises from 2008 and intervened on an even larger scale.
In March, the commercial banks proved unable to act as intermediaries in the market for normal U.S. Treasury bonds.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. Corrections on the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms were pushed aside.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed rescued the money market funds again.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but that never happened.
Moreover, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially providing a guarantee on the lines of "whatever it takes."
In 2008, the Fed and the U.S. Treasury Department had resisted the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages within the financial rescue package - the Troubled Asset Relief Program.
But in 2020, with the "Powell put," among other things, an explicit lower bound for corporate bond prices was established.
The predictable rebuttal to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We need not worry about systemic risks because the Fed and the U.S. Treasury Department will simply extinguish any new fire with another flood of money.
The problem, however, lies in the incentives these strategies have created.
Why bother using emergency funds or balance sheet room for purchases when prices are falling, providing liquidity, or treating a "fire sale" as an "opportunity" to buy?
The Fed will always overtake everyone and claim the profits.
Why issue stocks when you can simply take out a loan knowing that the state supports the debt or helps the company out of trouble, as was the case with airlines?
Why hesitate as an investor when it comes to buying dubious papers if their value is guaranteed by another "whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed during tough times?
No wonder America is sinking into debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will pick up the losses during the next downturn.
Student loans, government pensions, and mortgages accumulate and wait for their turn in Uncle Sam's rescue operation.
But every new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to put any more money into rescue operations, and people will not be happy with trillions of newly printed dollars.
If the expected rescue packages do not materialize, we will wake up in a major fire – and the fire department will be burned down.
In 2008, regulatory bodies and lawmakers at least recognized the moral hazard and worried that investors would profit in good times while taxpayers would bear the losses in bad times.
In 2020, it was all about self-congratulation regarding the rescue actions.
Exactly the Fed, which failed to see the risks of the subprime mortgage crisis in 2008 just as it did the pandemic in 2020 and now wants to conduct stress tests regarding "climate risks," will certainly also overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next bankruptcy, or any other disruptive event.
The Fed's regulators do not even ask about the mentioned events.
And while jargon about "connections," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles" is produced, it has not been possible to define "systemic" risk beyond making it a catch-all term that bestows comprehensive power on regulatory bodies.
Regulatory bodies will never be able to predict risks, measure the value of financial institution assets precisely, or ensure that enormous debts can always be paid off.
We need to reverse the basic premise of a financial system where the state always stands behind mountains of debt in bad times. And we need to do this before the fire department is tested.
Better regulation can bridge partisan divides.
The Left is correct when it argues that the big banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit few Americans.
However, it gets the cause wrong.
The enormous effort required to comply with regulations represents a significant barrier to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is pointless.
Regulations are either smart or dumb, effective or ineffective, full of unwanted consequences or well-designed.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and does not require regulatory bodies to have prophetic abilities.
The Fed has scandalously stopped companies in the narrow banking and payment services sectors that could have contributed to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before it commits to saving the planet and making amends for injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how inadequately it performs its fundamental duty of protecting the financial system.
